Muritala Ayinla Indications have emerged that the Lagos State Taskforce on Environmental and Special Offences (Enforcement ) Unit only needs Governor Babajide Sanwo-Olu’s order before auctioning off the 108 vehicles it has so far impounded during the course of its operations. This, development follows the ‘Court Order’ authorising the agency’s power to auction the 108 forfeited/abandoned vehicles to interested members of the public. A source within the Taskforce, who pleaded anonymity, said that the after obtaining court’s order; the agency must also get approval from the state governor, Mr Babajide Sanwo-Olu before going ahead with the planned auction. Speaking on the development, Taskforce Chairman,CSP Olayinka Egbeyemi said that 86 of the vehicles were forfeited and 22 were abandoned after being impounded by the enforcement team of the Agency in different parts of the state for driving against traffic (one-way) and committing other traffic offences. According to him, the public auction is scheduled to hold on Tuesday and Wednesday, December 3 and 4 at the Agency’s car park in Ikorodu. He said: “It was after the expiration of the 30-day public notice issued by the Agency in line with the dictates of the law to all owners of the 22 abandoned vehicles to claim them that the government obtained the court order to auctioned them to interested members of the public” “Let me commend the present administration for the on-going massive roads rehabilitation going on simultaneously across the State and to state clearly that motorists both private and commercial bus drivers should desist from driving against traffic (one-way) or causing traffic obstructions to other roads users with.” Meanwhile, the enforcement team of the Agency, led by the Chairman, over the weekend cleared all illegal trucks and abandoned vehicles causing traffic gridlock at ‘Guinness’ Ikeja/Ogba axis in line with the directive of the Lagos State Commissioner of Police, CP Hakeem Odumosu. CSP Egbeyemi commended the new Lagos State Police Commissioner for his pro-activeness in enforcing both the Lagos State Environmental Sanitation Laws and the Lagos State Transport Sector Reform Law 2018.